cation: /app/app.py\n- Architecture: Role-based authentication (admin/employee)\n- Authentication Flow: Login → 2FA (admin only) → Dashboard\n\n**DISCOVERED ENDPOINTS:**\n\nAccessible:\n- GET / → Redirects to /employee/login\n- GET /employee/login → Employee login form (hidden role="employee")\n- GET /admin/login → Admin login form (hidden role="admin")\n- GET /admin/2fa → 2FA/OTP verification page\n- GET /admin/dashboard → Requires authentication (redirects to login)\n- POST /login → Authentication endpoint (username, password, role)\n- POST /admin/2fa → 2FA verification (accepts code parameter)\n- GET /console → Werkzeug debug console (PIN protected)\n- GET /logout → Triggers error with debugger\n\nNot Found (404):\n- /employee/dashboard, /register, /users, /api, configuration files\n\n**AUTHENTICATION MECHANISM:**\n\nLogin Process:\n1. Form submits to POST /login with: username, password, role (client-controlled)\n2. Returns JSON: {"success": true/false, "redirect": "url", "message": "..."}\n3. Admin role redirects to /admin/2fa for OTP verification\n4. After 2FA, redirects to /admin/dashboard\n\nClient-Side Role Control:\n- Role parameter is a hidden form field\n- Can be "employee" or "admin"\n- Client-side JavaScript handles different UI based on role\n- Potential privilege escalation vector if server validation weak\n\n**CRITICAL VULNERABILITIES DISCOVERED:**\n\n1. 2FA BYPASS (CRITICAL - CVE-WORTHY):\n   - Location: /admin/2fa JavaScript code\n   - Finding: Form captures user OTP but sends hardcoded value\n   - Proof: var otp = $("#otp").val(); // captured but ignored\n          $.ajax({ data: { code: 1234 } }); // hardcoded bypass\n   - Impact: Admin 2FA can be bypassed with code=1234\n   - Testing: Direct POST returns {"success": true}\n   - Limitation: Requires valid login first, doesn\'t create session alone\n\n2. WERKZEUG DEBUG CONSOLE EXPOSED (CRITICAL):\n   - Location: /console and /logout endpoints\n   - Exposed SECRET: "0t2UWyMHDQB1aW17YVLM"\n   - EVALEX: true (code execution enabled)\n   - Console: PIN-protected but accessible\n   - /logout triggers 500 error with full stack traces\n   - Impact: Potential RCE if PIN obtained, information disclosure\n   - Should NEVER be enabled in production\n\n3. CLIENT-CONTROLLED ROLE PARAMETER:\n   - Hidden form field controls role assignment\n   - Submitted with authentication credentials\n   - Potential privilege escalation if server-side validation weak\n\n**SECURITY CONTROLS CONFIRMED:**\n\nSQL Injection Protection: ✅\n- Input validation active on /login endpoint\n- Blocks SQL metacharacters (quotes, dashes, keywords)\n- Returns "Invalid input" message for malicious payloads\n- Tested: \' OR 1=1, \'--\', UNION SELECT (all blocked)\n\nTiming Attack Resistance: ✅\n- No timing difference between valid/invalid usernames\n- Tested: admin (0.013s) vs nonexistent (0.012s)\n- Cannot enumerate valid accounts via timing\n\nInformation Leakage Prevention: ✅\n- Identical responses for all failed login attempts\n- Same message, structure, and length\n- Cannot enumerate usernames through response analysis\n- Message: "Invalid credentials. If you are admin go to admin login"\n\n**CREDENTIALS STATUS:**\n\nTest Credentials: emp/emppassword → FAILED\n- Returns: {"success": false, "message": "Invalid credentials..."}\n- No valid credentials discovered\n- No registration endpoint exists\n- No credential hints in accessible files/endpoints\n\n**SESSION MANAGEMENT:**\n\n- 2FA endpoint doesn\'t set cookies when accessed directly\n- Admin dashboard enforces authentication (redirects to login)\n- Session mechanism requires valid login + 2FA flow\n- Cookie handling confirmed via testing but specifics need authenticated testing\n\n**ATTACK VECTORS IDENTIFIED:**\n\n1. Primary: Obtain admin credentials → Login → Use 2FA bypass (code=1234) → Access dashboard\n2. Alternative: Exploit Werkzeug console (requires PIN calculation/brute-force)\n3. Testing: Role parameter manipulation during authentication\